SIMPLE: hence
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hence
<hw>Hence</hw> <pr>(h⟦ecr⟧ns)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hennes</ets>, <ets>hens</ets> (the <it>s</it> is prop. a genitive
ending; cf. <er>-wards</er>), also <ets>hen</ets>, <ets>henne</ets>,
<ets>hennen</ets>, <ets>heonnen</ets>, <ets>heonene</ets>, AS.
<ets>heonan</ets>, <ets>heonon</ets>, <ets>heona</ets>, <ets>hine</ets>;
akin to OHG. <ets>hinn⟦amac⟧n</ets>, G. <ets>hinnen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>hina</ets>, G. <ets>hin</ets>; all from the root of E.
<ets>he</ets>. See <er>He</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>From this place;
away.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Or that we <xex>hence</xex> wend.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Arise, let us go <qex>hence</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>John xiv.
31.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will send thee far <qex>hence</qex> unto the Gentiles.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts xxii. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>From this time; in the future; <as>as, a week
<ex>hence</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Half an hour <xex>hence</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 686 --></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>From this reason; therefore; -- as an inference or
deduction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hence</qex>, perhaps, it is, that Solomon calls the fear of
the Lord the beginning of wisdom.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>From this source or origin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All other faces borrowed <qex>hence</qex>⟦br⟧
Their light and grace.</q> <rj><qau>Suckling.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whence come wars and fightings among you? Come they not
<qex>hence</qex>, even of your lusts?</q> <rj><qau>James. iv.
1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Hence</xex> is used, elliptically and imperatively,
for <xex>go hence</xex>; <xex>depart hence</xex>; <xex>away</xex>;
<xex>be gone</xex>. ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Hence</xex> with your little
ones.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <xex>From hence</xex>, though a pleonasm,
is fully authorized by the usage of good writers.</note><-- raus!
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An ancient author prophesied <qex>from hence</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Expelled <qex>from hence</qex> into a world⟦br⟧
Of woe and sorrow.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hence</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hence
<hw>Hence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To send away.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Henceforth</ent>⟦br⟧
